The paper deals with modeling and analyzing biological networks, specifically the mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAPK) network. This falls under the category of systems biology, which is closely related to computational biology and bioinformatics. The paper uses symbolic computation methods, which are commonly used in the field of computer algebra systems (CAS) and symbolic computation (cs.SC). The paper also mentions graph theory, which is a subfield of computer science (cs.DM). Additionally, the paper discusses numerical continuation methods, which are commonly used in numerical analysis (cs.NA). Finally, the paper deals with the multistationarity of biological networks, which is a topic in mathematical biology (q-bio). Based on these factors, the most likely sub-categories are cs.SY (Systems and Control), cs.MS (Mathematical Software), q-bio.QM (Quantitative Methods), q-bio.TO (Tissues and Organs), and q-bio.MN (Molecular Networks).
